$ Windows service: Schedule

The *Task Scheduler*.

{ Run a powershell script at start up #task-scheduler-ps-at-startup

  The following sequence of Powershell commands configures the task schuduler such that it starts a powershell script when the system starts up:
code {
$act = → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/scheduledTaskAction/new      -execute powershell.exe -argument '-file c:\project-X\Health-monitor.ps1'
$trg = → Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/scheduledTaskTrigger/new     -atStartup
$prc = new-scheduledTaskPrincipal   -userId "→ Windows/security/SID/S-1-5/18[NT AUTHORITY\SYSTEM]" -logonType ServiceAccount
$set = new-scheduledTaskSettingsSet -executionTimeLimit (→ Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/timeSpan/new -seconds 0)  # Make sure task is not stopped if it runs longer than a given period.

→ Windows/PowerShell/command-inventory/noun/scheduledTask/register -taskName 'Health monitor'  -action $act -trigger $trg -settings $set -principal $prc # -runLevel Highest
code }

}

sa:

 `→ Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/schtasks_exe`is the *Task Scheduler Configuration Tool*. Its deprecated cousin is → Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/at_exe[`at.exe`].
  -
 `→ Windows/dirs/Windows/System32/taskschd_msc`

 `→ Windows/registry/tree/HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE/Software/Microsoft/Windows-NT/CurrentVersion/Schedule/TaskCache/Tree`

  → Windows/automatically-started-programs

